                        <div class="spotlight-title" id="section-1">Introduction</div> 
                        <div class="spotlight-summary"> 
                             This page provides an overview of ImageNow administration best practices for ensuring optimal performance and stability for the ImageNow product suite. While the complete list of best practices is targeted to enterprise-wide deployments, they can be adopted in smaller deployments to ensure peak performance. 
                        </div>  
                                        
                        <div class="spotlight-title" id="section-2">Server Architecture Overview </div> 
                        <div class="spotlight-summary"> 
                                When reviewing performance and stability for ImageNow, it is helpful to take a look at the architecture supporting the application. 
                        </div>
                        
                        
                        
                        <img style="WIDTH: 864px; HEIGHT: 533px"  SRC= "{!URLFOR($Resource.Perceptive_Sites, 'images/performance.jpg')}" alt="Server Architecture Overview" />
                        <br />
                        <br />
                         <p>The ImageNow Server computer is responsible for responding to end user requests and notifications. The core process, inserver, is responsible for handling user requests from the clients (ImageNow Client, WebNow, and Interact for MS Office). Additional core processes, such as Batch Agent, Workflow Agent, and Retention Agent, handle supporting tasks in the background. These agents process resource-intensive tasks, which removes the long-running tasks from the user threads.</p>
                         <br />
                         <p>The extended server agents, such as Content Server and Recogition Agent, can be installed on a remote server computer to free up system resources for the inserver process and the other core server agents. Utilizing a remote agent computer can keep the ImageNow application server hardware focused on the user requests while isolating resource-intensive task processing.  The additional remote agent computer can be a virtual machine, which allows for adding or removing additional resources as business needs change.</p>
                         <br />
                         <p>ImageNow Server components that can be run remotely to the ImageNow Server computer: </p>
                         <br />
                         <dl> 
                             <dd>Business Intelligence</dd>
                             <dd>Content Server (inserverFT) – 6.6 and higher</dd>
                             <dd>Conversion Module (INMAC) </dd>
                             <dd>Direct Print</dd>
                             <dd>File Processing Agent (inserverFP)</dd>
                             <dd>Forms Server</dd>
                             <dd>Mail Agent (inserverMail)</dd>
                             <dd>Output Agent (inserverOutput)</dd>
                             <dd>Recognition Agent (inserverRec)</dd>
                             <dd>Message Agent (inserverMA)</dd>
                             <dd>User Replication Agent (inserverUR)</dd>
                             <dd>WebNow Server</dd>
                           </dl>
                         <br />
                            ImageNow Server agents that cannot be run remotely to ImageNow Server computer:
                            <dl> 
                                <dd>Alarm Agent (inserverAlarm)</dd>
                                <dd>Batch Agent (inserverBatch)</dd>
                                <dd>External Messaging Agent (inserverEM)</dd>
                                <dd>File System Agent (inserverFS)</dd>
                                <dd>Job Agent (inserverJob)</dd>
                                <dd>Message Queueing Agent (inserverMQ)</dd>
                                <dd>Monitor Agent (inserverMonitor)</dd>
                                <dd>Notification Agent (inserverNotification)</dd>
                                <dd>OSM Agent (inserverOSM)</dd>
                                <dd>Retention Agent (inserverRetention)</dd>
                                <dd>Task Agent (inserverTask)</dd>
                                <dd>Workflow Agent (inserverWorkflow)</dd>
                             </dl>
